                                <date>1958</date>. С. <biblScope unit="page">??–??</biblScope>.</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><xi:include href="../encodingdesc.xml" parse="xml"/></teiHeader><text><body><entry xml:id="entry_baslyq" xml:lang="os"><form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>baslyq</orth></form><form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>basluq</orth><form type="variant"><orth>baslæq</orth></form></form><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>башлык</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>bashlyk</q></abv:tr></sense><abv:exampleGrp><abv:example><quote>fælæværttæ kodtoj wædy ræstæǵy æǧdawmæ gæsgæ; ḱī cuqa, ḱī k˳yræt, ḱī baslyq</quote><abv:tr xml:lang="ru"><q>сделали подарки согласно обычаю того времени: кто черкеску, кто бешмет, кто башлык</q></abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en"><q>[they] made presents according to customs of that time: who [presented] Circassian coat, who [presented] beshmet, who [presented] bashlyq</q></abv:tr><bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Сека"/><biblScope>39</biblScope></bibl></abv:example></abv:exampleGrp><etym xml:lang="ru">Из <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>bašlyq</w> <gloss><q>башлык</q></gloss></mentioned> (образовано от <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>baš</w> <gloss><q>голова</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>lyq</w></mentioned> — суффикс). Отсюда же <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><lang/> <w>baślyq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/> <w>bašlyq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>bašluǧi</w></mentioned> и др. Известно также в южных и восточных %bрусских%b диалектах.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>8</biblScope></bibl>.</etym><etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>bašlyq</w> <gloss><q>bashlyk</q></gloss></mentioned> (derived from <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>baš</w> <gloss><q>head</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>lyq</w></mentioned> — suffix). Also from here <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><lang/> <w>baślyq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/> <w>bašlyq</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>bašluǧi</w></mentioned> etc. The word is also known in South and East Russian dialects. %n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>8</biblScope></bibl>.</etym></entry></body></text></TEI>